# The Conversion of Prutha

## Scene summary (from gm-assist, verbatim)

#### Vukradin successfully convinces one of the remaining orcs to abandon Talos and follow the path of Lathander.
- Vukradin makes a final persuasive speech to orc 2 (the money-demanding orc), rolling a 17 against the orc's wisdom save of 12. The orc is persuaded.
- The orc sets down his great axe. He observes the Drow cleric wreathed in sunlight: "Lathander, power, beyond doubt. Lathander, all-powerful." He then rushes toward Valphine and pledges himself.
- The DM generates a name from an orc name generator: Prutha. The party briefly debates giving him a "Lathandrian conversion name"; Valphine's player suggests "Thrall," which Vukradin's player objects to on grounds of dignity. Prutha it remains.
- Prutha reveals his backstory: his great uncle was the clan's shaman, killed by Talosians to break the band's resistance and force recruitment. The shaman was called "Weak, Abomination, and Thunder Meat." Prutha fought for Talos out of necessity, never killing by choice across three skirmishes.
- Prutha states: "Uncle wright, make clear, either fight or die. I fought."
- Prutha offers an unprompted piece of his great uncle's philosophy: "Great uncle taught one thing. Dawn comes for everyone, even those born in shadow." The table is visibly moved.
- Vukradin rolls a 27 Insight, reading Prutha's genuine emotion. The DM reveals Prutha hasn't blown the whistle in a very long time.
- Prutha produces a bone whistle and explains that his clan's tradition was to greet the sunrise each morning with it. He blows it. He begins to cry: "My uncle blew this whistle. They killed him for it. I did not blow it until now."
- Vukradin's player quietly notes in character: "The power of the sun has returned to rescue your people."
- Valphine rolls a Religion check (a low roll, with Bardic inspiration bringing it to 12) and gains the insight that the bone whistle ritual can be woven into her evolving Lathandrian rites. The DM notes Lathander seems closer to Valphine, not further, despite — or perhaps because of — her unorthodox methods.
- Prutha confirms his view on the remaining Talosians: those who no longer follow Talos can be spared; those who still follow Talos must be dealt with. "Convert or die" is agreed upon, with varying degrees of enthusiasm around the table.
- The party loots a potion of greater healing from the fallen anchorite's body. (Party now holds two potions of greater healing — one carried before this session, one looted here — plus one potion of superior healing and one scented potion of healing.)
- Valphine and Brewbarry string up the anchorite's corpse as a warning. Prutha thinks it is "totally cool." Vukradin disapproves but says nothing; Vukradin's player is engrossed in a theological discussion with Prutha.
- The DM notes that Prutha's conversion reflects something meaningful: the Eastern Orcs of his clan had a sub-cult with sun associations, and the Talosians had suppressed it violently. Valphine's approach — ordered, purposeful, unapologetically powerful — resonates with that buried tradition in a way that a gentler sermon might not have.
- Valphine heals Xanth for 13 points (restoring him to within 1 hit point of his maximum after the 14 points of lightning damage he sustained). She also attempts to use Lathander's Blessing on Boney — to Boney's apparent discomfort.

